1️⃣ Engines Must Be Separated

The most important things when working with Codex are:

legal-engine

draft-engine

audit-engine

These three should never be mixed.

Reason:

Ensures test independence

Minimizes the impact of audit logic modifications

Replaceable legal APIs
2️⃣ Integrations are an "external dependency isolation area."

External APIs are only called here.

Example:

integrations/law-api/client.ts

Do not fetch directly from the engine.
→ Inject via interface.

This allows mocking in tests.

3️⃣ The docs folder is the reference document for Codex.

Codex reads the entire repo.

Therefore:

SPEC.md

DATA_MODEL.md

TASKS.md

AGENTS.md

These four must exist in the root or docs folder.

4️⃣ The database is clearly separated.

Schema file

Migration history

Seed data

Include laws/audit samples in the seed folder. (No hardcoding of operational data)

5️⃣ Test Structure
tests/unit/legal-engine.test.ts
tests/unit/audit-engine.test.ts
tests/integration/full-flow.test.ts

Audit risks must be included in unit tests.

🔒 Structure for Future Expansion

If expanding to a multi-agency SaaS in the future:

packages/tenant-manager/
packages/role-permission/

Additional details are possible.
